[2]
Date: 8 May 2002 09:46PM
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Mercury [edited]
http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=ct20020508214641465B200226


Bacteria in Durban harbour causes man's death
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A fisherman has died from an unusual cholera-type bacteria infection after
wading in shallow water in Durban harbour, raising concern about the use of
the harbour for recreation activities.

A 55-year-old Woodlands resident, picked up the infection while collecting sand
prawns near the Fynnland angling club about 10 days ago.

His fishing friend, was also admitted to hospital with a blood infection after
wading at the same spot, near the mouths of the Amanzimnyama and Umhlatuzana
canals.

Though the news has raised fears about the quality of harbour water, medical
experts said the cases were unusual because both men had small cuts or wounds
on their legs, through which bacteria entered directly into their bloodstreams.

Tests suggested it was a different type of bacteria

The bacteria which killed [this patient] is common in warm salt-water estuaries
in several parts of the world but does not often affect healthy people unless
they have open wounds or eat uncooked seafood.

A City Health department spokesperson has declined to comment until the case
has been investigated further, but it is believed that officials have collected
water samples near the club to establish whether there are unusually high
levels of bacteria.

[The patient] became ill within days of wading in the harbour and died last
week as a result of poisoning by _Vibrio vunificus_, a cousin of the cholera
virus.

His friend, became ill a few days afterwards and was admitted to McCord
Hospital with bulbous lumps under his arm. He was discharged on Wednesday.
A spokesperson said staff suspected initially that [his fishing mate] might
have the same infection as [him] but tests suggested it was a different type of
bacteria.

There was also an unconfirmed report on Wednesday night that a young boy picked
up a blood infection through a cut on his neck while swimming at Addington
beach, allegedly leading to the subsequent discovery of old syringes and
bandages on the beach in front of Addington hospital.

Although the _Vibrio vulnificus_ bacteria which attacked [the patient] is a
common salt-water organism human fatalities are rare. However, in cases where
direct blood infections were the result of cuts or open wounds exposed to sea
water, the fatality rate can be as high as 50 percent according to American
government Centres for Disease Control and Prevention. [[see moderator comments
below. The CDC reference site can be found at
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dbmd/diseaseinfo/vibriovulnificus_t.htm> - Mod.MPP]

A spokesperson for McCord and a Durban microbiologist both confirmed that
Vibrio vulnificus infections were rarely reported in this country. The
microbiologist felt it would be misleading to create hysteria by suggesting
that there was an outbreak of "a beastly killer bug" in Durban harbour.
[Byline: Tony Carnie]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to Chin's Control of Communicable Diseases Manual, infection with
_Vibrio vulnificus_ produces septicemia in persons with chronic liver disease,
chronic alcoholism or hemochromatosis, or those who are immunosuppressed. The
disease appears 12 hours to 3 days after eating raw or undercooked seafood,
especially oysters. One third of the patients are in shock when they present
for care or develop hypotension (low blood pressure) within 12 hours after
hospital admission. Three quarters of patients have distinctive, bullous skin
lesions (large blister-like); thrombocytopenia (low platelets) is common and
there is often evidence of disseminated intravascular coagulation. Over 50
percent of patients with primary septicemia die; the mortality rate exceeds 90
percent among those who become hypotensive. _V. vulnificus can also infect
wounds sustained in coastal or estuarine waters; wounds range from mild self
limited lesions to rapidly progressive cellulitis (skin infection) and myositis
that can mimic clostridial myonecrosis (muscle tissue death) in the rapidity of
spread and destructiveness.

The organism is a halophilic lactose positive (85 percent of isolates) marine
vibrio similar to _V. parahaemolyticus biochemically. It is a free-living
autochtonous flora of estuarine environments. It is the most common agent of
serious infections caused by the genus vibrio in the USA (in coastal areas of
the USA the annual incidence of infection is 0.5 per 100 000 population). It
has been reported from Japan, Korea, Taiwan, Israel, Spain and Turkey.
(A review of the literature included additional case reports and or _V.
vulnificus isolates from Singapore, Hong Kong, Malaysia, Korea, Thailand,
Australia, Saudi Arabia, Czech Republic, Denmark, French West Indies, Mexico ,
Brazil and Senegal. If I missed a few locations, my apologies -- there were
510 references related to _V. vulnificans). A few selected references are
presented below.

This appears to be the first case reported from Southern Africa, and with the
case reports from Senegal (ref. 5) this appears to be the second case report
from the African continent. - Mod.MPP]

[1: Kumamoto KS, Vukich DJ. Clinical infections of Vibrio vulnificus: a case
report and review of the literature. J Emerg Med. 1998 Jan-Feb;16(1):61-6.
2: Cook DW, Oleary P, Hunsucker JC, Sloan EM, Bowers JC, Blodgett RJ, Depaola
A. Vibrio vulnificus and Vibrio parahaemolyticus in U.S. retail shell oysters:
a national survey from June 1998 to July 1999. J Food Prot. 2002 Jan;65(1):79-87.
3: Melhus A, Larsson C, Schliamser S. [Vibrio vulnificus. A marine bacterium
with lethal potential] Lakartidningen. 2001 Aug 8;98(32-33):3400-2.
4: DePaola A, McLeroy S, McManus G. Distribution of Vibrio vulnificus phage
in oyster tissues and other estuarine habitats. Appl Environ Microbiol. 1997
Jun;63(6):2464-7.
5: Dieng MT, Niang SO, Ly F, Bathily T, Ndiaye B. [Necrotizing dermatitis due
to Vibrio Vulnificus] Ann Dermatol Venereol. 2001 May;128(5):653-5.
6: Chan WL, Chan CH, Chan TY. Vibrio vulnificus septicaemia and necrotizing
fasciitis after a prick from the dorsal fin of a tilapia. Trans R Soc Trop Med
Hyg. 1999 Mar-Apr;93(2):174.
7: Bisharat N, Agmon V, Finkelstein R, Raz R, Ben-Dror G, Lerner L, Soboh S,
Colodner R, Cameron DN, Wykstra DL, Swerdlow DL, Farmer JJ 3rd. Clinical,
epidemiological, and microbiological features of Vibrio vulnificus biogroup 3
causing outbreaks of wound infection and bacteraemia in Israel. Israel Vibrio
Study Group. Lancet. 1999 Oct 23;354(9188):1421-4.
8: Chuang YC, Yuan CY, Liu CY, Lan CK, Huang AH. Vibrio vulnificus infection
in Taiwan: report of 28 cases and review of clinical manifestations and
treatment. Clin Infect Dis. 1992 Aug;15(2):271-6.]
